# `std.agent.mcp` — expose agent tools over MCP

The agent SDK (`std.agent`) and the MCP stack (`std.mcp`) define tools independently.
`serveAgentToolsMcp` is the bridge in the **provider direction** (the rozum
`integration.md` "one tool definition, two consumers" goal): take the `AgentTool`s an
app already declared for its in-process agent loop and serve them over MCP, so an
**external** agent can drive the very same tools — no second tool definition.

Each MCP call arrives with JSON-decoded args as `Map[String, Any]`; we re-serialize
them to the JSON string an `AgentTool.handler` expects (`jsonStringify`), run the
app's handler (which validates + executes), and map its `ToolResult` back to an MCP
result. The two `ToolResult` types never meet by name — the agent result is consumed
by field, the MCP result is produced via `Tool.text` / `Tool.error`.

```scalascript
[mcpServer, serveMcp, Tool, Transport, Content](std/mcp/server.ssc)
[McpClient](std/mcp/client.ssc)
[AgentTool, agentTool, toolOk, toolError](std/agent.ssc)
[jsonStringify](std/json.ssc)

// Parse a tool-call arguments JSON object into the Map the MCP client expects.
// Binds to the json plugin's `jsonParse` intrinsic; tool args are always JSON objects.
extern def jsonParse(s: String): Map[String, Any]

// ─── Provider direction: expose AgentTools over MCP ──────────────────────────

/** Serve a list of agent tools over MCP on `transport`, then block (per `serveMcp`).
 *  `Transport.Stdio` blocks until stdin closes; `Transport.Http(port)` listens (JS). */
def serveAgentToolsMcp(tools: List[AgentTool], transport: Transport): Unit =
  mcpServer { srv =>
    tools.foreach { t =>
      srv.tool(t.name, t.description) { args =>
        val result = t.handler(jsonStringify(args))
        if result.isError then Tool.error(result.contentJson)
        else Tool.text(result.contentJson)
      }
    }
  }
  serveMcp(transport)

// ─── Consumer direction: use an MCP server's tools as agent tools ────────────

/** Flatten an MCP `ToolResult`'s content into the JSON/text string an agent tool returns. */
def mcpResultText(content: List[Content]): String =
  content.map { c =>
    c match
      case Content.Text(t) => t
      case _               => ""
  }.mkString

/** Wrap every tool of a connected MCP server as an `AgentTool`, so the agent loop can call
 *  them. The handler forwards the model's JSON args to `client.callTool` and maps the MCP
 *  result back (`Tool` error flag → `toolError`). Requires a jvm/js backend (`McpClient`). */
def mcpToolSource(client: McpClient): List[AgentTool] =
  client.listTools().map { td =>
    agentTool(td.name, td.description, jsonStringify(td.schema)) { argsJson =>
      val result = client.callTool(td.name, jsonParse(argsJson))
      val text = mcpResultText(result.content)
      if result.isError then toolError(text) else toolOk(text)
    }
  }
```
